<TEXT>
westinghouse electric corp next year will 
begin operating the federal governments aging atomic reactor 
complex in south carolina that produces nuclear weapons material 
joseph salgado acting deputy secretary of energy announced 
thursday that the department of energy had selected 
pittsburghbased westinghouse for the 5year operating contract 
worth an estimated 67 billion 
westinghouse was competing with martin marietta corp for the 
right to replace the du pont co as operator of the savannah river 
plant du pont which built the plant and operated it for more than 
30 years announced last fall it would not renew its contract when 
it expires next april 
the selection process resulted in the choice of the single 
proposer which i believe will operate srp in the best interest of 
this nation salgado said 
all three operating reactors at the plant currently are shut 
down because of safety concerns or maintenance operations 
westinghouse operates six other doe nuclear facilities the 
company will begin operations at the savannah river plant on nov 
1 working with du pont during a fivemonth transition period 
doe spokeswoman chris sankey said du pont employees working at 
the plant will be guaranteed continued employment with westinghouse 
john c marous chairman and chief executive officer of 
westinghouse said in a statement that his company will be 
committed to total quality of all phases of operation 
energy secretary john herrington last month recommended the 
savannah river plant as the site for a newly designed reactor to 
produce all the tritium needed for the nations nuclear weapons 
program he also recommended construction of a smaller nuclear 
reactor to produce weapons materials in idaho 
the new reactors eventually would replace the three aging 
reactors at srp and one at the hanford nuclear reservation in 
washington state 
</TEXT>
