<DOCNO> AP880909-0033 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the reagan administration is moving swiftly to 
ban the use of tissue from intentionally aborted fetuses in 
research before a special national institutes of health advisory 
committee meets on the matter 
gary l bauer president reagans assistant for policy 
development told health and human services secretary otis r bowen 
he wanted the secretarys comments on the proposed executive order 
by today 
the nih panel formed at the direction of a top official in 
bowens department begins a twoday meeting sept 14 to consider 
the issue 
a copy of bauers memo dated sept 2 along with a copy of the 
draft executive order that reagan would sign was obtained thursday 
by the associated press 
campbell gardett an hhs spokesman confirmed that the documents 
had been received by bowen 
theres no comment at this time on the draft order which is 
under review said gardett 
the issue arose last april when nih scientists sought approval 
to conduct experiments in which brain tissue from freshly aborted 
fetuses would be transplanted to patients suffering from 
parkinsons disease 
surgeons in mexico city reported last january that they had 
injected such tissue from a miscarried fetus into the brains of two 
parkinsons sufferers with promising results 
there have been reports of researchers in other countries 
employing the emerging fetal tissue transplant techniques which 
also could have applications in many other diseases 
although miscarried fetuses have long been used in more 
conventional research areas the new techniques which require 
fresh tissue to be effective open up a new rash of ethical 
questions 
parkinsons disease causes gradual loss of muscle control and is 
potentially fatal the fetal tissue is believed to work by 
stimulating production of dopamine a brain chemical that people 
suffering from parkinsons lack 
much of the opposition to the new research has come from people 
who oppose abortion under all circumstances the draft order 
circulated by bauer says final regulations shall be issued by 
nov 1 1988 one week before election day 
the white house instructed bowen last month to enforce stringent 
new rules against federally financed family planning clinics that 
counsel abortion in any cases not covered by two court orders which 
ban enforcement over much of the country 
however federal officials acknowledged that the instructions 
would have little immediate impact since they would apply only to 
grant applications received after oct 1 and that only a handful 
will be up for renewal even then 
private family planning leaders maintained the white house edict 
was a political statement to energize antiabortion forces prior to 
the republican national convention 
bauers memo said the fetal research order is intended to 
protect unborn and newborn children from experimentation research 
and organ transplantation except in cases where the unborn or 
newborn child would itself directly benefit by any such 
procedures 
dr robert e windom the assistant hhs secretary for health 
rejected a proposed nih project last april in which scientists 
would implant fetal tissue into patients with parkinsons disease 
windom instructed nih director james b wyngaarden to appoint an 
outside advisory committee to examine the ethical medical and 
legal implications of using tissue from intentionally aborted 
fetuses 
that prohibition issued in april which is still in force did 
not ban continuing research on tissue from fetuses from 
miscarriages or stillbirths nor would the proposed executive order 
it shall be the policy of the federal government to the 
extent permitted by law that an unborn or newborn child who has 
died as a result of an induced abortion shall not be used for 
purposes of research or transplantation says the draft order 
although the impact was not immediately clear the draft 
apparently would attempt to inhibit such activities by private 
researchers who benefit from federal funds 
activities and procedures not in conformance with the policies 
above may not receive federal funds nor may such activities be 
conducted by federal agencies or departments or in facilities 
governed by federal law to the extend permitted by law said one 
section 
a few conferences have been held by ethicists and researchers on 
the new technology but no clear consensus has emerged in the 
scientific community about how to proceed 
a letter published in science magazine last year by participants 
in a seminar at case western university is one of the clearest 
statements on the potential questions 
that letter signed by neurosurgeons ethicists and lawyers 
concluded that there are similarities to using tissue from fetal 
remains and using tissue from adult cadavers but it went on to say 
there are dissimilarities that merit careful consideration 
the letter recommended for example that there should be a 
clear separation between decisions related to the acquisition of 
tissue and decisions regarding the transplanting of tissue into a 
recipient 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880909-0034 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
commodore oliver hazard perry they didnt give 
up your ship 
the brigantine niagara restored to fighting trim and still 
flying perrys battle flag dont give up the ship is 
scheduled to be returned to the great lakes on saturday exactly 
175 years after perrys fleet defeated the british in the battle of 
lake erie 
perry would recognize his old ship this is as exact a 
restoration as there can be said melbourne smith an annapolis 
md marine architect who dismantled the niagara and rebuilt it to 
historical specifications 
the 182foot 278ton ship restored for the third time with 
38 million in state and private money in dry dock at this port 
city will be outfitted by next spring with 118foot and 113foot 
masts square rigging about 22000 square feet of polyester sail 
and 20 aluminum cannons 
then it is to tour the great lakes and east coast ports as 
pennsylvanias official flagship 
the first uss niagara was one of six small ships built at erie 
during the war of 1812 and put under perrys command to break a 
british blockade of american great lakes ports and to defend the 
northwest territory 
on sept 10 1813 perrys nineship squadron met six british 
vessels under commodore robert heriot barclay in a short but fierce 
battle near putinbay ohio that left 135 british and 123 
american casualties 
perrys flagship the uss lawrence was disabled by british fire 
and perry transferred to the niagara where he hoisted his famous 
blueandwhite battle flag and attacked again the niagara helped 
break the british battle line and forced barclay to surrender 
we have met the enemy and they are ours two ships two brigs 
one schooner and one sloop perry reported to his superiors 
the niagara served as a station ship in erie until 1820 when 
she was scuttled in nearby misery bay the ship was raised by erie 
citizens in 1913 and restored for a great lakes tour to celebrate 
the 100th anniversary of perrys victory she was restored again in 
the 1930s and 1940s 
the latest niagara incorporates 42 pieces of the original ship 
some within view for visitors smith said the original wood is aged 
and not strong enough for structural use 
it will be obvious he said 
in 1813 a gang of about 300 shipwrights blacksmiths and other 
craftsmen and laborers directed by new york shipbuilders adam and 
noah brown hired on at erie and built perrys fleet in three 
months there were no sawmills in erie which then had only 500 
inhabitants and craftsmen cut hewed and squared the unseasoned 
wood by hand 
it was all green wood from around here it wouldnt last two 
years smith said but it didnt matter this was a throwaway 
boat for war 
smiths modern crew of about 60 working over 99 days included 
shipwrights and carpenters experienced in restoring old ships they 
were assisted by laborers from the pennsylvania conservation corps 
a job training program for disadvantaged youth 
they worked in a dockyard where perrys smaller gunboats were 
built in 1813 the niagara and lawrence were built nearby 
according to project spokeswoman maura mclaughlin 
the niagaras new 18pound carronades which are stubby cannons 
for shortrange use and two 12pound long guns will be cast at an 
erie foundry of aluminum to save 10 tons of weight on deck the 
navy removed the original cannons before sinking the niagara 
ships like this werent very safe to sail they were top 
heavy smith said but it was wartime and it didnt matter in 
wartime you do dangerous things 
smith estimated a crew of about 35 will be needed to sail the 
restored ship as it tours the great lakes beginning next summer 
the state does not plan to give rides or to rent the ship 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

