a nuclear regulatory commission vote next week 
is likely to remove a major hurdle in the long quest by operators 
of the seabrook nh nuclear power plant to obtain a lowpower 
operating license 
none of the commissioners objected to the proposed rules change 
at a staff briefing thursday and nrc chairman lando w zech jr 
said afterwards that he likely would take the staffs 
recommendation and support it a vote is scheduled for next friday 
the proposal would allow seabrook to receive a license to 
conduct tests at 5 percent power capacity without having a system 
in place to notify residents within 10 miles of the reactor of an 
accident 
it is highly unlikely that members of the general public would 
be exposed to dangerous levels of radiation following an accident 
at low power the staff said in a 23page report to the 
commissioners 
the rule if adopted would allow the commission to reverse a 
february ruling by the atomic safety and licensing appeal board 
that blocked a lowpower license after sirens were removed from the 
massachusetts municipalities within the plants 10mile zone 
new hampshire yankee the plants operator was forced to remove 
the sirens after a federal appeals court sided with state and local 
officials massachusetts gov michael dukakis and other plant 
opponents wanted the sirens removed because they believe no 
evacuation system can adequately protect nearby residents 
under the new rule new hampshire yankee still would need a 
notification system for a fullpower license the company has 
suggested truckmounted sirens and sirenequipped helicopters as 
replacements 
