whitney ray petersen hasnt been born yet 
but doctors are preparing to give him a new heart in an operation 
performed only once before officials say 
the fetus carried by cynthia petersen who is 33 weeks pregnant 
suffers from a lethal heart defect called hypoplastic left 
ventricle in which the left chamber of the heart does not develop 
mrs petersen and her husband daymon who have selected whitney 
ray as the name for their boy when he is born said thursday they 
would fly to loma linda university medical center to await a 
suitable donor heart 
if an appropriate donor heart becomes available the baby will 
be delivered by caesarean section and the heart will be 
transplanted immediately 
baby paul from canada is the only other baby with 
hypoplastic left ventricle to have had a transplant right after 
birth the baby was operated on at loma linda 11 months ago and is 
growing normally officials said 
mrs petersens obstetrician found the abnormal fetal heart beat 
during a prenatal examination and referred her to dr greggory de 
vore director of the intermountain fetal diagnostic and treatment 
center at lds hospital here 
most babies with the fetuss condition die within the first 
three to four weeks of life de vore said 
twenty infants have undergone human heart transplants at loma 
linda and 16 are having healthy normal childhoods said hospital 
spokeswoman anita rockwell 
but de vore said those were the ones lucky enough to find a 
donor and that half the babies die before a donor can be located 
the petersens hope to improve the odds by starting the search 
before birth 
we know there is only a 50 percent chance they will even 
locate a donor but we are optimistic petersen said 
because a newborns immune system isnt developed it is not 
yet keyed in to reject a donor organ and the transplant is more 
likely to take de vore said although rejection still is possible 
the petersens have a 5yearold girl and a 2yearold boy 
