turks are expressing concern over 
longterm problems that may have been caused by allowing about 
60000 kurdish refugees fleeing iraq to enter turkey in the past 
week 
primary concern is over security at a time when turkey slowly 
has been gaining the upper hand in a war of attrition against its 
own band of kurdish guerrillas known as the kurdish labor party 
the marxist group aims to set up an independent state in the 
southeast provinces 
intelligence and military officials fear that members of the 
party often denied sanctuary or assistance by turkeys kurdish 
minority of 10 million in the region can now find a safe haven to 
organize and recruit in the new refugee camps near the border 
today the foreign ministry denied reports that several thousand 
kurdish refugees given sanctuary in turkey had later been forced to 
go to iran 
it is out of the question to send any of the refugees to 
another country against their will we categorically deny these 
reports foreign ministry spokesman nazim belger said 
on sunday the leftist istanbul daily cumhuriyet quoted a local 
opposition politician in semdinli township near the iraqi border as 
saying that 4000 to 5000 kurdish refugees had been sent to iran 
against their will 
the report was later picked up by foreign news media 
security forces are taking precautions to prevent infiltration 
of the camps by the kurdish labor party regional governor hayri 
kozakcioglu has said 
since 1984 about 700 people have died in clashes between 
turkish government forces and the guerrillas 
