<TEXT>
one of the radar operators on board the uss 
vincennes was so nervous in the moments before the cruiser shot 
down an iranian airliner that he tried and failed five times to 
punch a button providing radar images of the plane a navy 
investigator said today 
the problem was one of a series of stresscaused errors which 
led to the us destruction of the jetliner which killed 290 people 
on july 3 rear adm william m fogarty told the house armed 
services committee 
the radar operator finally got the correct image on his sixth 
try fogarty said 
the navy will try to make its training more realistic but 
theres no way to simulate combat and eliminate the stresscaused 
errors that led to the us action service officials told the 
panel in a second day of hearings on the incident 
unless you get shot at youre not trained in combat 
fogarty said thursday 
fogarty headed the navy investigation into the shooting down of 
iran air flight 655 by the guided missile cruiser uss vincennes on 
july 3 in the persian gulf the vincennes command thought it was 
firing at an iranian f14 military jet when it launched two 
missiles and killed all 290 persons aboard the airliner 
fogartys investigation found the sophisticated aegis tracking 
equipment aboard the vincennes worked well but the data was 
misread by crew members who were taking the fouryearold ship into 
combat for the first time 
although the equipment functioned as it should navy officials 
told congress they plan to add new radio equipment to ships 
assigned to the persian gulf area and is upgrading the ships 
tracking sensors 
fogartys report was released three weeks ago and he repeated 
its general conclusions to senators who were generally supportive 
i believe this was a tragic mistake said sen james exon 
dneb echoing other legislators 
fogartys investigation concluded that the vincennes which 
carries some of the navys most sophisticated electronic sensors 
and weaponry was adequately trained when it sailed into the 
persian gulf region in late may 
she entered the gulf trained he said adding that unless 
you get shot at youre not trained in combat 
capt george n gee director of the navys surface combat 
systems division said the service doesnt give specific stress 
training to our people although that is something were going 
to look at 
fogarty detailed a confused and highstress situation in the 
vincennes combat center the iranian plane was approaching as the 
ship was concluding a firefight with iranian gunboats that had 
attacked the vincennes helicopter while the chopper was on patrol 
we try not to be hysterical we try not to be yelling 
fogarty said although on that day there were a lot of items 
that caused the excitement level to rise there were people 
raising their voices above what we would like to see 
the vincennes guns were firing as it made a highspeed turn to 
bring its aftdeck guns to bear fogarty said 
amid the confusion one unidentified officer called out a 
warning to the vincennes skipper capt will c rogers that the 
approaching plane might not be military 
the officer was standing behind rogers and called out possible 
comm air commercial aircraft and rogers acknowledged the 
warning with a wave of his hand fogarty said 
but other factors prompted rogers to order two missiles 
fired at the jet in the mistaken belief it was an iranian military 
plane 
those factors included the justfinished firefight the 
assumption that any plane coming from iran was a potential military 
threat intelligence warnings about possible iranian attacks over 
the july 4 weekend and the memory of the frigate uss stark fogarty 
said 
the stark was hit by an iraqi missile in the persian gulf in may 
1987 killing 37 us seamen the starks top officers were 
disciplined for not firing their weapons to protect the ship 
in the vincennes shooting two errors never could be explained 
satisfactorily fogarty said including the mistaken belief the 
iranian airbus was descending and the initial identification as an 
f14 
iran air 655 was climbing continually from the time it took off 
from bandar abbas and was at 13000 feet when it was struck by the 
two missiles eight miles from the vincennes 
officers in the combat center correctly identified the airbus as 
climbing until the plane came to within 15 miles of the vincennes 
when they inexplicably concluded the plane began descending toward 
the cruiser fogarty said officials have said the aegis sensors 
were functioning correctly 
the misreading of the altitude was one of the most puzzling 
aspects fogarty said but the investigators were never able to 
figure out how that occurred the investigation was unsuccessful 
in satisfactorily reconciling the discrepancy between electronic 
data which showed the plane was still climbing and shouted verbal 
statements that it was descending he said 
one radar operator in the combat center said the approaching 
plane had sent a mode 2 transmission a transmitter used only 
by military planes civilian aircraft use a mode 3 
transmission and the airbus transmitted information only on mode 
3 the investigation noted 
a nearby warship the frigate sides had tracked the airbus as a 
possible iranian military plane but it concluded the plane was not 
a threat fogarty said 
