<TEXT>
imprisoned and exiled for 18 years 
former prime minister u nu once appeared to have accepted his 
position as burmas forgotten man 
that is until friday when the 82yearold politician sallied 
forth in an attempt to lead antigovernment forces to restore the 
democracy he was forced to surrender 26 years ago 
u nu who spent the last few years translating buddhist 
scriptures said friday he has formed a government to challenge the 
authoritarian system imposed by military leader ne win in 1962 
but his chances of success are not known burma is on the brink 
of chaos and the powerful military is still intact in addition 
the opposition appears fragmented 
in his favor diplomats said u nu is probably the least 
controversial of the opppositon leaders but they added much will 
depend on his advisers 
born in the irrawaddy delta town of wakema u nu joined the 
nationalist drive against british colonialism at rangoon 
university where he was elected president of the influential 
student union 
with the assassination of his close friend independence fighter 
aung san u nu took over the leadership of a free burma 
u nu served as prime minister for most of the period between 
1948 and 1958 when ne win took charge of a caretaker government u 
nu was reelected prime minister in 1960 but toppled two years 
later by the ambitious general who imprisoned him for the next 
four years 
u nus record was mixed he was unable to curb muscleflexing 
generals and squabbling politicians crime soared and some of 
burmas many ethnic minorities began their now fourdecadelong war 
against the central government 
but the economy improved and u nu maintained the trust of other 
ethnic groups both the press and the political arena were alive 
with debate 
one of the original members of the third worlds nonaligned 
movement u nu laid the foundations of burmese neutralism but 
unlike ne win he maintained open relations with the worlds 
superpowers 
in 1955 u nu proudly told stunned soviet leaders that he had 
broken the back of the domestic communist movement the same year 
he lectured washington about opening diplomatic relations with 
communist china 
in 1969 u nu left burma and spent the next 11 years as an exile 
in thailand and india from bases along the thaiburmese border he 
attempted to lead an antine win insurgency he even sent a small 
aircaft over rangoon to drop leaflets calling for an uprising 
but u nu proved a poor insurgent and in 1974 thailand asked him 
to leave the country indira gandhi then prime minster of india 
gave him with a yellow stucco house on a hillside in the city of 
bhopal where he lived a quiet life newspaper articles called him 
burmas forgotten man 
he returned to burma in 1980 under a general amnesty offered by 
his archrival ne win promising to stay out of politics and devote 
the rest of his life to translating buddhist works into burmese 
a writer of plays poems novels and political works u nu also 
has been a keen translator among his renderings into burmese have 
been the works of karl marx and dale carnegies how to win 
friends and influence people 
