<TEXT>
boston university plans to revive dormitory rules 
barring students from having overnight guests of the opposite sex 
and reducing the amount of alcohol brought into their rooms 
twenty years ago there was a move toward openness and now 
the pendulum is swinging back said university spokesman kevin 
carleton many people including students their parents and 
college administrators have seen that wide open dorms of years 
past did not work well for the serious student 
the new parietal rules came partly in response to complaints 
from parents including a letter from the mother of a female 
student whose roommate frequently entertained a boyfriend 
overnight carleton said 
ronald l carter dean of students declined to comment until 
after the rules are officially released sept 15 
at present as many as four guests can sign into a dormitory 
room and stay overnight if all roommates and resident assistants 
agree 
under the new guidelines which carleton said go into effect in 
late fall guests must hand in identification cards and leave the 
dormitory by 11 pm on weekdays or 1 am on weekends 
overnight stays by members of the same sex will be allowed if 
roommates agree but members of the opposite sex will not be 
allowed overnight officials said 
greg lang editor of the college newspaper the daily free 
press said friday that we sense a lot of students are very 
unhappy with the plan which he said would be difficult to 
enforce 
compared to a lot of issues on campus this really hits home 
with the majority of students lang said if they do go ahead 
and put this into practice therell be a lot of students opposed 
to it and who knows what will happen right now its a 
waitandsee situation 
parietal rules were abandoned by many american colleges and 
universities including bu in the 1960s and 1970s at the same 
time that coeducational dormitories were instituted such rules 
remain mostly at smaller colleges with strong religious 
affiliations 
carleton said the applicant pool for bus freshman class has 
increased dramatically in recent years allowing the university to 
choose serious students who prefer a traditional lifestyle the 
3650 students in this years freshman class were selected from 
23921 applicants 4000 more than last year 
were providing the kind of housing serious students want and 
need carleton said we are recognizing our obligation as 
university administrators and not as the operators of hotels or 
apartment houses 
