<TEXT>
imagine this work week 
leave los angeles at 815 pm and fly 5 hours to honolulu 
rest the second day but leave late that night at 1 am which 
is 4 am los angeles time for the 8hour flight to auckland 
new zealand where you wait 90 minutes then fly three more hours to 
sydney australia after a days rest in australia you do the same 
thing in reverse landing back in los angeles seven days after you 
left 
or consider this schedule 
leave boston at 615 am fly two hours to cincinnati leave an 
hour later on a 4hour flight to los angeles twelve hours after 
landing youre back in the cockpit flying all night to cincinnati 
and after an hour on the ground on to newark arriving back on 
the east coast 26 hours after you left 
it is schedules like these the first flown by united airlines 
crews the second by delta airlines that pilots say wear them 
down sometimes leaving them groggy and prone to mistakes 
what were doing with these schedules is taking human beings 
and saying lets get the maximum out of them said one united 
captain interviewed by the associated press who asked not to be 
identified out of concern for his job as a result weve got 
crews who are in rough shape out there 
yet another united captain who makes transpacific flights said 
his most recent sixday tour of duty went like this 
1015 am arrive los angeles international airport for 1135 
jumbo jet trip to tokyo go through paper work check flight plans 
weather fuel passenger load 
flight promises to be particularly heavy requiring unscheduled 
fuel stop in alaska several passengers fail to show making extra 
stop unnecessary but threatened schedule change and a mixup 
getting departure clearance mean plane is pushed away from the gate 
40 minutes late 
1235 pm after starting the engines taxiing out to runway 
going over checklist plane takes off 
after liftoff we run a sterile cockpit until top of climb 
the captain says that means all business no chitchat no pa 
announcements we check the instruments seeing that the systems 
are running as we expect and check the inertial navigation system 
to make sure it is tracking with ground navigation aids 
the plane leaves the california coast north of san francisco and 
passes over the aleutian islands from then on the flight is 
routine the crew makes regular position checks watches the 
navigational instruments listens to an emergency frequency chats 
with other planes and eats crew meals are better than coach but 
not as fancy as first class 
as plane approaches tokyo about 10 hours after takeoff there 
are more checklists and instructions from air traffic controllers 
you have to screw up your level of concentration because 
insidiously you often are not aware of your fatigue the captain 
says 
248 pm tokyo time following day plane lands at narita 
international airport pilots cockpit time between leaving the 
terminal in los angeles and parking in tokyo block to block as 
they say is 11 hours and 33 minutes 
the crew is on duty for 30 minutes more finishing up paper 
work they clear customs and immigration and are picked up by a bus 
for the 15minute ride to a hotel 
the captain stays up a couple of hours more having dinner 
reading and unwinding he finally goes to sleep at 8 pm which is 
5 am los angeles time he sleeps five or six hours wakes up well 
before dawn he has breakfast reads and exercises at noon he 
tries unsuccessfully to sleep again 
5 pm bus picks up crew for 630 departure for seattle 
before this tour is over the pilot flies back to tokyo via 
anchorage alaska then returns to los angeles when he gets home 
he sleeps 13 hours straight 
such schedules are relatively common and uniformly grueling 
the problem say officials is that to schedule the 18500 daily 
flights to get people where they want when they want to remain 
competitive and costeffective some pilots must fly through the 
night across multiple time zones then come back eight hours later 
and do it again 
typically each airline presents its monthly flights to both 
human schedulers and computers programmed to consider the vagaries 
of economics fuel consumption regulations contracts and human 
and equipment limits 
men and machines come up with possibilities that are 
doublechecked 
we take a look at it based on the safety issues said george 
hof head of flight operations at american airlines the 
computer in optimizing the costs in crewing the series of flights 
will take a look at the duty time available and cram a lot of 
flying into that 
once approved the crew lists are put up for bid the pilots bid 
for schedules based on their desirability and hourly pay rate 
those who fly the bigger faster planes get paid more pilot wages 
range from about 70000 a year to a top of 160000 
according to the airline pilots association the average pilot 
is in the cockpit about 80 hours a month and spends another 80 
hours on duty preparing for flights or waiting for passengers to 
load and unload 
this total of 160 hours is crammed into an average of 16 days a 
month 
management and pilots agree there is little way to avoid some of 
the overnight multiple time zone schedules that test pilots 
endurance 
youre not going to work it all out said dick stone a 
delta captain and chairman of the pilots unions human performance 
committee we work silly hours and thats just the way the 
business is 
