here are some facts and figures on the maghreb in north africa 
the countries and the land algeria morocco tunisia libya 
and mauritania make up the maghreb or the arab west in north 
africa they cover about 2341000 square miles onefifth of the 
african continent this is about twothirds the area of the 
continental united states 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people the total population is about 68 million and 99 
percent are moslems virtually all speak one of several dialects of 
arabic most are descendants of the berber tribes who were the 
original inhabitants before the arrival of the arabs most of the 
people are farmers and herders most of the population is 
concentrated around the main cities casablanca marrakech 
algiers oran constantine tunis and tripoli 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the economy algeria libya and tunisia have economies based on 
exports of oil and gas tunisia also has a substantial income from 
tourism and from the export of wine and citrus fruit tourism wine 
and citrus fruit also are important in morocco but the largest 
earner of foreign currency is the export of phosphates worth about 
400 million in 1986 mauritania mines about 10 million tons of 
iron ore annually at the zouerate mines and catches 35000 tons of 
fish onetenth of the total in mauritanian waters currencies and 
their equivalents in us money algerian dinar 17 cents 
moroccan dirham 13 cents tunisian dinar 130 libyan dinar 
30 cents mauritanian ouguiya 2 cents 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history christianized under the roman empire the area became 
part of the islamic world in the eighth century in the 19th 
century it came under french spanish and italian colonization on 
independence after world war ii the area came mostly under 
totalitarian or absolutist regimes morocco and algeria fought a 
brief border war in 1963 followed by a long quarrel over the 
western sahara tunisia and libya quarrelled over citizens rights 
and over oil prospecting in the mediterranean algeria and libya 
have a longpending territorial dispute in may they began work on 
a framework for a confederation 
</TEXT>
