<TEXT>
a nationwide shortage of rubber gloves appears 
to be easing but you wouldnt know it from talking to estella 
williams 
the obstetricsgynecology nurse at st lukesroosevelt hospital 
center isnt even using rubber gloves because they have become too 
expensive she gets vinyl ones oversized instead 
you can pull a glove on and it rips sometimes youre washing 
instruments and you find out it has a hole in it so what good is 
that she said recently 
ms williams employer says there is no hospitalwide problem 
with gloves but across the country the aids crisis has led to a 
dramatic increase in the use of gloves resulting in shortages 
high prices and the importation of millions of defective gloves 
a leap in production has alleviated the shortage somewhat in 
recent months and most forecasters say it will continue to ease as 
new factories in the united states and southeast asia gear up 
production 
but some people say the shortage could worsen again if the fear 
of aids prompts people in other countries to become as fastidious 
about covering their hands as americans have become 
if all the industries that have physical touching with people 
start to use gloves theres not enough gloves in the world 
ever said edward skonezny president of american consolidated 
products inc in santa ana calif who imports gloves and has an 
interest in promoting the idea that the shortage could worsen again 
the increased glove use stems from a new wariness about bare 
hands in a diseaseconscious society so many people are wearing 
gloves now that those who need them most doctors dentists 
nurses and the like are having trouble getting their hands in 
them 
in the united states gloves are being worn by people ranging 
from hairdressers toll station attendants and prison guards to 
foodservice workers even though the centers for disease control 
says there are no reports of aids being spread by food preparation 
the aids virus surprisingly is very difficult to transmit 
a lot of this is hysteria or paranoia or whatever you want to 
call it said chuck fallis a spokesman for the national centers 
for disease control in atlanta 
its almost a habit youre putting on gloves even when you 
dont know if youll be doing anything that would require them 
said dr robert auerbach a new york dermatologist 
when my local bartender gives me a glass of whisky with a 
glove on ill really start to get worried said ted presler 
vice president for marketing at guthrie latex inc in tucson 
ariz the us unit of malaysiabased kumpulan guthrie berhad 
so far at least glove use has not caught on overseas the way 
it has in the united states 
in britains national health service the system of socialized 
medicine workers generally do not use gloves except in the 
operating room for lab work and when coming in contact with blood 
and other body fluids 
japan has had only 90 aids cases since 1985 when the first was 
diagnosed and glove use remains low although it is growing 
rapidly an importer in osaka said demand had doubled in the last 
two years 
africa has the worlds worst aids problem but the continents 
poverty and lack of good medical care are likely to limit the use 
of gloves there 
southeast asia the world center of rubber production is a big 
winner from the boom in glove use prices have nearly tripled for 
latex the milky liquid form of rubber from which gloves are made 
and glove factories are opening by the dozens 
malaysia the worlds biggest rubber producer expects to churn 
out 2 billion gloves from 30 factories this year and aims for 4 
billion from 60 or more factories next year said dr lim sow 
ching head of the malaysian rubber research and development 
boards economic planning division 
that much production could drive prices back down nearly to 
their precrisis levels even with increasing use of gloves also 
gearing up glove production are indonesia thailand taiwan and 
china as well as the united states 
global demand is hard to estimate but malaysia estimates 
current annual demand is about 13 billion to 15 billion gloves a 
year 
some glove users have never felt the pinch of the shortage 
because they have been sheltered by usbased medical supply 
companies which kept prices down to avoid alienating customers 
the reputable manufacturers of latex medical products have not 
taken advantage of the situation at all our major concern is 
really to increase capacity said eugene freed senior vice 
president for marketing at ansellamericas of tinton falls nj 
the nations biggest maker of nonsterile exam gloves 
a lack of factories is the main cause of the glove shortage 
along with a lack of centrifuges which spin excess water out of 
raw latex latex prices although they have roughly tripled still 
account for a relatively small portion of the price of gloves 
increased condom use has not had much effect on latex prices 
because they use less of it a pound of latex makes 60 gloves but 
nearly 300 condoms 
speculators as well contributed to the shortage by buying up 
supplies and withholding latex from the market said douglas kerr 
vice president of production at national latex products co in 
ashland ohio 
kerr said he was not accusing his own suppliers of speculation 
but he believes that kind of activity drove latex prices up 
similar accusations have been made about the glove market 
they saw this as a commodity like sugar or rice they got in 
quick and they got out quick these people had money said edward 
sun vice president for marketing in the new york office of at 
general pacific international corp a trading company with 
headquarters in hong kong 
hoarding is also contributing to the shortage kerr said he 
compared it to the gasoline crisis of the early 1970s when people 
kept their tanks topped off 
prices for a box of 100 gloves rose in the spot market to 15 a 
box and some desperate doctors and dentists reportedly paid more 
than 20 a box since then prices have fallen back below 10 a box 
distributors say 
problems with the quality price and availability of gloves all 
stem from the panic over contamination and even many in the 
industry believe the fears are overblown 
i think weve created our own crisis here i can say from my 
own point of view its been a very nice crisis but i dont know 
that its helped the cause of health care any said jack bennett 
sr president of medical companies of america inc in phoenix 
ariz 
