<TEXT>
a federal jury friday awarded a woman 
nearly 9 million in finding that gd searle amp co made 
intentional misrepresentations of the copper7 intrauterine device 
leading to the womans sterility 
the jury also decided the company was negligent in its testing 
of the copper7 but not in its design or manufacture of the 
copper7 worn by esther kociemba 
mrs kociemba 30 of elk river was awarded 7 million in 
punitive damages 1 million for emotional distress and 750000 
for pain and disability 
the jury decided mrs kociembas husband william did not 
experience the loss of consortium as a direct result of his wifes 
use of the copper7 and did not award him damages 
jurors refused to comment on the verdict 
searle attorney paul strain of baltimore said the verdict will 
be appealed 
it was a complex case there was a lot of emotional rhetoric 
in this case but the safety of the copper7 will be established by 
judge renner in this case or on appeal strain said 
some 500 lawsuits have been filed over the copper7 the most 
widely used iud in the united states before being withdrawn from 
the us market in january 1986 in the midst of the litigation 
searle won 15 of the previous 18 cases to be decided but 
kociemba lawyers have said that none of the previous cases included 
as many documents or deposition testimony as this one kociemba 
lawyer roger p brosnahan said before the trial started that it 
would be the first real trial involving the copper7 
were gratified that a jury that has finally heard all the 
evidence has come to a decision we think is just brosnahan said 
friday 
asked if the damages award was fair he said that is 
difficult to assess money cant recover fertility money cant 
give you the children 
mrs kociemba was not in court when the verdict was read her 
whereabouts were not immediately known 
the three previous cases lost by searle awarded damages totaling 
550000 strain said earlier including one damages award of 
250000 that is being appealed 
mrs kociemba used a copper7 for just under 1 years in 1977 
and 1978 she claims that the iud triggered a pelvic infection two 
weeks after insertion and that the infection scarred her fallopian 
tubes leaving her sterile 
her lawyers throughout the 3month trial sought to establish 
through the testimony of searle employees and former employees and 
through the companys internal documents that searle knew of 
potential health risks with the copper7 but did not adequately 
disclose those risks to doctors or the public 
the jury was in its 10th day of deliberations friday after 
hearing testimony that began may 17 and ended aug 25 
the lead attorney for the plaintiffs michael ciresi of 
minneapolis alleged in his closing argument that searle was 
negligent in designing the device with a tailstring he said 
provided a haven for bacteria that produced pelvic infections 
calling searle a corporation which allows greed to be its 
guiding beacon he said the company rushed the copper7 to market 
without proper testing he charged it was sold to women without 
adequate warning that it could cause pelvic inflammatory disease 
and without warning that it was too large for many young women who 
had never given birth 
but strain said the company exceeded fda requirements in 
marketing copper7 he said ciresi did not even prove that mrs 
kociemba suffered from pelvic infection let alone that it was 
caused by the copper7 
